dvantageous. Through historical analysis, he explains how child soldiering developed out of Mao's protracted war theory and the militarization of youth during the twentieth century. A case study of the civil war in Sierra Leone, which details the brutality involved when children are forced to fight, is included.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aChild soldiersvStatistics. 0aChild soldiers. 0aChildren and warzSierra LeonevCase studies. 0aChildren and war. 0aMilitary art and sciencexMoral and ethical aspectsvCase studies. 0aTacticsvCase studies. 0aTacticsxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aWarxMoral and ethical aspectsvCase studies. 4aAnthropology and Archaeology : Anthropology. 4aPolitics and Law : International Relations. 4aPolitics and Law : Politics. 4aSociology : Sociology of War. 4aSociology : Violence. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2018z978311149142440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143847200340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438472003423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438472003/original  a978-3-11-149142-4  SUNY Press eBook Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles